WEBVTT

00:04.088 --> 00:05.798
Hey, Leonard, check this out.

00:10.469 --> 00:12.346
Leonard, she's doing it again.

00:12.930 --> 00:15.975
I think it upsets Sheldon
when you play with the food.

00:16.142 --> 00:20.146
No, it upsets Sheldon when she
willy-nilly takes it from the containers...

00:20.313 --> 00:23.107
...without regard
for its equitable distribution.

00:23.274 --> 00:26.319
This is essentially
why you have famine in India.

00:28.487 --> 00:31.073
You want me to put it back?

00:31.991 --> 00:33.701
- Leonard?
- It upsets Sheldon...

00:33.868 --> 00:36.162
...when you play with the Sheldon.

00:38.122 --> 00:41.083
What's up, my nerdizzles?

00:41.542 --> 00:44.378
Raj, Sheldon, I want you
to meet my girlfriend, Bernadette.

00:44.545 --> 00:45.921
- Hello.
- Leonard, Penny.

00:46.088 --> 00:48.507
- You know my girlfriend, Bernadette.
- Yeah. Hey.

00:48.674 --> 00:51.302
Bernadette,
say "fo'shizzle" to my nerdizzles.

00:51.886 --> 00:53.929
I don't think I can.

00:54.305 --> 00:56.974
I don't have Howard's street cred.

00:58.309 --> 01:01.937
I hope it's all right, I told Bernadette
she could join us for dinner.

01:02.104 --> 01:05.107
- Sure. The more, the merrier.
- No, that's a false equivalency.

01:05.274 --> 01:06.651
More does not equal merry.

01:06.817 --> 01:09.945
If there were 2000 people in this
apartment, would we be celebrating?

01:10.112 --> 01:11.697
No, we'd be suffocating.

01:12.114 --> 01:13.449
- Sheldon.
- Don't "Sheldon" me.

01:13.616 --> 01:16.118
- We ordered for five people, not six.
- It's fine.

01:16.285 --> 01:18.371
We'll put it on the table, family-style.

01:18.537 --> 01:21.248
Oh, sure. Why don't we put our hands
behind our backs...

01:21.415 --> 01:23.793
...have an old-fashioned
eating contest?

01:24.377 --> 01:27.630
Relax. It'll be fine. Sit down, you guys.

01:29.006 --> 01:30.508
ALL EXCEPT BERNADETTE: No.
- What?

01:32.677 --> 01:34.428
Oh, yeah, you can't sit there.

01:34.595 --> 01:36.889
- Why not?
- That's where Sheldon sits.

01:37.056 --> 01:38.391
He can't sit somewhere else?

01:40.142 --> 01:42.937
In the winter, that seat's close enough
to the radiator...

01:43.104 --> 01:45.398
...so he's warm
yet not so close that he sweats.

01:45.564 --> 01:47.858
In the summer,
it's in the path of a breeze...

01:48.025 --> 01:49.902
...created by opening windows there.

01:50.069 --> 01:53.489
It faces the television at an angle
that isn't direct so he can talk...

01:53.656 --> 01:56.951
...yet not so wide
that the picture looks distorted.

02:00.246 --> 02:03.332
Perhaps there's hope for you after all.

02:30.818 --> 02:33.821
- I love your shoes.
- Oh, thanks. They are cute, aren't they?

02:33.988 --> 02:35.698
- Where'd you get them?
- Shoes for Less.

02:35.906 --> 02:40.202
- I've been meaning to go over there.
- Oh, great selection, great prices.

02:40.536 --> 02:43.456
My mother was right. Hell is real.

02:44.498 --> 02:47.460
Come on, Sheldon,
let the women-folk chat.

02:50.296 --> 02:51.338
Women-folk?

02:52.047 --> 02:53.841
Gals? Chicks?

02:54.008 --> 02:56.218
Utero-Americans?

02:57.678 --> 03:00.806
- Just eat your dinner.
- Don't take him too seriously.

03:00.973 --> 03:04.435
A lot of what he says
is intended as humor.

03:04.977 --> 03:07.062
Yeah, well,
I don't think it's very funny.

03:07.229 --> 03:10.691
Me neither,
but he just lights up when I laugh.

03:13.319 --> 03:15.654
Howard, never let her go.

03:17.490 --> 03:20.326
Leonard, Howard says you're working on
fundamental tests...

03:20.493 --> 03:23.829
- ...of quantum mechanics.
- I am. Are you interested in physics?

03:23.996 --> 03:25.164
I find it fascinating.

03:25.498 --> 03:27.333
If I hadn't gone into microbiology...

03:27.500 --> 03:31.670
...l probably would have gone
into physics or ice dancing.

03:32.463 --> 03:35.341
My tests of the Aharonov-Bohm
quantum interference effect...

03:35.508 --> 03:37.259
...have reached an interesting point.

03:37.468 --> 03:39.845
We're testing phase shift
due to electric potential.

03:40.012 --> 03:42.223
- That's amazing.
SHELDON [CHUCKLES]: Yes.

03:42.389 --> 03:45.017
Leonard's work is nearly
as amazing as third graders...

03:45.184 --> 03:48.395
...growing lima beans
in wet paper towels.

03:49.396 --> 03:51.732
While I appreciate the "oh, snap"...

03:51.899 --> 03:55.194
...I'm uncomfortable having
your moist breath in my ear.

03:58.697 --> 04:01.909
Are you going to try to set up
the voltages using tunnel junctions?

04:02.993 --> 04:04.078
Yes, I am.

04:04.245 --> 04:07.540
- Wanna see a simulation on my laptop?
- Oh, yeah. Show me.

04:07.873 --> 04:12.127
In microbiology, the most exciting thing
I get to work with is yeast.

04:13.379 --> 04:14.964
SHELDON: Howard?
- Yeah?

04:15.130 --> 04:17.716
Your shoes are delightful.

04:20.135 --> 04:22.429
Where did you get them?

04:22.888 --> 04:25.641
- What?
- Buzzinga. I don't care.

04:32.398 --> 04:33.816
[VIDEO GAME PLAYING]

04:33.983 --> 04:38.070
Ha-ha. Eat my dust,
racially stereotypical plumber.

04:41.031 --> 04:43.617
That's not fair.
I got stuck behind a tree.

04:43.784 --> 04:45.578
And a cow and a penguin.

04:46.745 --> 04:52.126
Face it, dude, whether it's a real car
or a virtual cartoon car, you can't drive.

04:52.418 --> 04:55.629
- Just need a little more practice.
- What you need is cheat codes...

04:55.796 --> 04:58.173
...motor skills and a genie
who grants wishes...

04:58.340 --> 05:00.968
...to little boys
who suck at "Mario Kart."

05:01.927 --> 05:02.970
[KNOCK ON DOOR]

05:04.096 --> 05:06.015
Sheldon,
can I talk to you for a second?

05:06.181 --> 05:08.601
It's not about shoes, is it?

05:08.767 --> 05:10.811
I don't think
I could go through that again.

05:10.978 --> 05:13.606
- It's not about shoes.
- Then speak.

05:13.772 --> 05:17.151
- Um, actually, can we do it in private?
- All right.

05:18.110 --> 05:19.653
Go away.

05:21.488 --> 05:24.325
I agree, it's rude,
but she asked for privacy.

05:25.367 --> 05:29.121
Thanks, Raj.
Okay, so here's the thing.

05:29.288 --> 05:32.708
I was wondering if you could
maybe teach me a little physics.

05:33.459 --> 05:36.670
- A little physics?
- Yeah.

05:36.837 --> 05:39.840
There's no such thing.
Physics encompasses the entire universe.

05:40.007 --> 05:42.384
From quantum particles to supernovas.

05:42.593 --> 05:45.679
From spinning electrons
to spinning galaxies.

05:45.846 --> 05:47.973
Okay, cool,
I don't need the PBS special.

05:48.724 --> 05:51.560
I wanna know enough
so I can talk to Leonard about his job.

05:51.727 --> 05:52.895
Like Bernadette does.

05:53.103 --> 05:56.023
- Why can't Leonard teach you?
- Because I wanna surprise him.

05:56.190 --> 05:58.150
Can't you surprise him
in some other way?

05:58.317 --> 06:02.363
For example, I'm sure he'd be delightfully
taken aback if you clean your apartment.

06:03.364 --> 06:05.491
Come on, Sheldon,
this is important to me.

06:05.658 --> 06:07.660
This would be
a massive undertaking...

06:07.826 --> 06:10.371
...and my time
is both limited and valuable.

06:10.537 --> 06:12.873
You're sitting here
playing video games all day.

06:14.166 --> 06:15.501
Okay, point.

06:17.127 --> 06:18.837
What sort of foundation do you have?

06:19.004 --> 06:21.256
Did you take any science classes
in school?

06:21.423 --> 06:23.384
Sure. I did the one with the frogs.

06:26.512 --> 06:29.264
The one with the frogs.

06:29.431 --> 06:33.727
It was pretty cool. A lot of the girls
threw up. I gutted that thing like a deer.

06:33.894 --> 06:36.730
No. I'm sorry, Penny. I don't think so.

06:36.897 --> 06:39.692
Oh, come on, a smart guy like you?
It'll be a challenge.

06:39.858 --> 06:42.653
You could make it like an experiment.

06:43.529 --> 06:45.531
Interesting.

06:45.698 --> 06:50.244
I suppose if someone could teach
sign language to Koko the gorilla...

06:50.911 --> 06:53.288
...l could teach you
some rudimentary physics.

06:53.455 --> 06:57.543
Great. It's a little insulting, but great.
I'll be Koko.

06:57.710 --> 07:00.629
Mm. Not likely. Koko learned to understand
over 2000 words.

07:00.796 --> 07:04.049
Not one of which
had anything to do with shoes.

07:06.093 --> 07:09.304
Hey, fellas,
this is my girlfriend, Bernadette.

07:09.471 --> 07:11.807
My girlfriend, Bernadette.

07:12.182 --> 07:14.435
- Who are all those people?
- I have no idea.

07:15.894 --> 07:17.896
- Hey, Leonard.
- Hi.

07:18.063 --> 07:20.566
Look, it's Howard
and his girlfriend, Bernadette.

07:20.733 --> 07:24.069
Thought I'd give the little woman
a tour of the old salt mines. Heh.

07:24.737 --> 07:29.283
He doesn't mean salt mines.
He means where he works.

07:30.576 --> 07:32.911
Yeah, no, I got it.

07:33.787 --> 07:36.248
- So how's your experiment going?
- Terrific.

07:36.415 --> 07:40.252
Getting the electron accelerator set up.
We should be ready day after tomorrow.

07:40.419 --> 07:43.338
- Boy, I'd love to see that.
- You're welcome to come.

07:43.505 --> 07:45.507
Really? That'd be great.

07:45.716 --> 07:47.301
How exciting is that?

07:47.468 --> 07:49.803
Like Hanukkah in July.

07:50.763 --> 07:52.264
Do they have that?

07:54.141 --> 07:57.978
- No.
- Oh, you got me again.

07:58.145 --> 08:00.105
[BOTH CHUCKLE]

08:01.356 --> 08:04.818
This isn't non-fat yogurt.
This is fatty-fat fat.

08:05.736 --> 08:07.154
Excuse me.

08:07.321 --> 08:09.281
- Could you grab me another napkin?
- Sure.

08:09.448 --> 08:10.532
Thanks, honey.

08:11.867 --> 08:13.952
All right. What is your deal?

08:14.286 --> 08:15.287
Excuse me?

08:15.454 --> 08:18.999
Inviting my girlfriend
to come see your electron accelerator?

08:19.166 --> 08:20.667
Yeah, so?

08:21.001 --> 08:25.464
Wow, you really are a piece of work.

08:25.631 --> 08:27.633
It's not enough
you get the prom queen...

08:27.800 --> 08:30.636
...you have to get the head
of the decorating committee too?

08:31.136 --> 08:34.473
- What are you talking about?
- Look, don't play innocent with me.

08:34.640 --> 08:39.353
I practically invented using
fancy lab equipment to seduce women.

08:39.978 --> 08:44.817
- Has it ever worked?
- Not so far, but that's not the point.

08:44.983 --> 08:47.528
Howard, relax.
I am not interested in your girlfriend.

08:47.694 --> 08:51.782
I hope not,
because you don't wanna mess with me.

08:57.079 --> 08:59.164
I'm crazy.

09:01.166 --> 09:03.043
I believe you.

09:04.837 --> 09:07.005
<i>SHELDON:
Research journal, entry one.</i>

09:07.172 --> 09:12.010
<i>I'm about to embark on one of the great
challenges of my scientific career:</i>

09:12.845 --> 09:15.347
<i>teaching Penny physics.</i>

09:16.515 --> 09:20.060
<i>I'm calling it Project Gorilla.</i>

09:21.603 --> 09:24.398
- Hey, Sheldon.
- Come in. Take a seat.

09:25.566 --> 09:27.818
<i>Subject has arrived.</i>

09:28.026 --> 09:31.196
<i>I've extended a friendly,
casual greeting.</i>

09:31.363 --> 09:32.781
Ready to get started?

09:32.948 --> 09:34.616
One moment.

09:38.245 --> 09:42.082
<i>Subject appears well-rested
and enthusiastic.</i>

09:42.749 --> 09:45.586
<i>Apparently, ignorance is bliss.</i>

09:47.421 --> 09:50.382
All right, let us begin.

09:51.049 --> 09:54.428
- Where's your notebook?
- Um, I don't have one.

09:54.595 --> 09:56.930
How are you gonna take notes
without a notebook?

09:57.097 --> 09:58.891
I have to take notes?

09:59.057 --> 10:01.143
How else are you gonna study
for the tests?

10:01.351 --> 10:04.938
- There's gonna be a test?
- Tests.

10:07.232 --> 10:11.278
Here. It's college-ruled.
I hope that's not too intimidating.

10:14.573 --> 10:15.949
- Thank you.
- You're welcome.

10:16.116 --> 10:18.285
Now, introduction to physics.

10:18.911 --> 10:20.913
What is physics?

10:21.079 --> 10:25.125
Physics comes
from the ancient Greek word "physika."

10:27.419 --> 10:30.505
It's at this point
that you'll wanna start taking notes.

10:31.924 --> 10:34.927
Physika means the science
of natural things.

10:35.093 --> 10:39.014
And it is there in ancient Greece
that our story begins.

10:39.431 --> 10:42.017
- Ancient Greece?
- Ah. If you have questions, raise your hand.

10:42.184 --> 10:43.769
[CLEARS THROAT]

10:44.144 --> 10:47.481
It's a warm summer evening,
circa 600 B.C.

10:47.648 --> 10:51.526
You've finished your shopping
at the local market or agora.

10:55.322 --> 10:57.282
And you look up at the night sky.

10:57.449 --> 11:00.953
And there you notice
some of the stars seem to move...

11:01.119 --> 11:05.791
...so you name them <i>planetes</i>
or wanderer.

11:12.172 --> 11:13.298
Yes, Penny?

11:13.465 --> 11:16.176
Does this have anything to do
with Leonard's work?

11:16.510 --> 11:21.556
This is the beginning of a 2600-year
journey we're going to take together...

11:23.016 --> 11:26.478
...from the ancient Greeks
through Isaac Newton to Niels Bohr...

11:26.645 --> 11:28.146
...to Erwin SchrÃ¶dinger...

11:28.313 --> 11:31.817
...to the Dutch researchers
that Leonard is currently ripping off.

11:33.443 --> 11:35.988
- Twenty-six hundred years?
- Yeah, give or take.

11:36.154 --> 11:41.410
As I was saying, it's a warm summer
evening in ancient Greece--

11:41.576 --> 11:44.204
- Yes, Penny.
- I have to go to the bathroom.

11:44.371 --> 11:48.166
- Can't you hold it?
- Not for 2600 years.

11:57.759 --> 12:00.429
<i>SHELDON".
Project Gorilla, entry two.</i>

12:00.595 --> 12:03.056
<i>I am exhausted.</i>

12:19.197 --> 12:20.574
- Howard?
- Uh-- Huh?

12:20.741 --> 12:22.784
It unhooks in the front.

12:23.410 --> 12:26.330
Oh, that explains a lot.

12:28.665 --> 12:29.958
[DOOR OPENS THEN CLOSES]

12:30.125 --> 12:33.253
MRS. WOLOWITZ:
Howard, I'm home.

12:33.420 --> 12:35.464
Of course.

12:35.630 --> 12:37.966
MRS. WOLOWITZ:
Senior fitness was canceled.

12:38.133 --> 12:41.345
It turns out you can forget
how to ride a bike.

12:42.471 --> 12:47.476
I'm fine, but, oy,
did Sam Harpootian eat gravel.

12:47.851 --> 12:49.519
That's great, Ma.

12:49.686 --> 12:52.230
MRS. WOLOWITZ: What's great
about an 80-year-old Armenian man...

12:52.397 --> 12:55.025
...with half his chin scraped off?

12:55.650 --> 12:57.611
- I guess I should go.
- No, don't move.

12:57.778 --> 13:00.906
Hey, Ma,
can I have lamb stew for dinner?

13:01.073 --> 13:04.785
MRS. WOLOWITZ: Lamb stew?
I'd have to go to the supermarket.

13:04.951 --> 13:08.497
Please? I got a real hankering.

13:10.082 --> 13:15.253
MRS. WOLOWITZ: Oh, I can't say no
to my little tushy-face.

13:15.545 --> 13:18.256
<i>- I'll</i> be back soon.
- Thanks, Ma.

13:21.093 --> 13:24.429
MRS. WOLOWITZ: Do you want the
regular peas or the Le Sueur?

13:24.596 --> 13:27.432
Always Le Sueur peas
with lamb stew.

13:27.599 --> 13:31.311
MRS. WOLOWITZ: You're right.
When you're right, you're right.

13:33.021 --> 13:37.025
- What if they're out of the Le Sueur?
- Then get the regular!

13:37.609 --> 13:40.153
MRS. WOLOWITZ:
All right. You don't have to yell.

13:40.320 --> 13:41.696
[DOOR CLOSES]

13:41.905 --> 13:43.865
Sorry about that.

13:44.574 --> 13:45.617
[CELL PHONE CHIMING]

13:46.827 --> 13:49.663
- Let me just put that on vibrate.
- I'm already on vibrate.

13:49.830 --> 13:51.415
[MAKES VIBRATING SOUND]

13:51.957 --> 13:53.542
Okay, now, that one I got.

13:55.252 --> 13:57.754
Howard, did you say something
to Leonard about me?

13:57.921 --> 13:58.964
What do you mean?

13:59.131 --> 14:03.176
He says if I go see his experiment
tomorrow, it might weird you out.

14:03.343 --> 14:04.636
Really? He said that?

14:04.970 --> 14:08.849
- You're not jealous of Leonard, are you?
- Me? No.

14:09.015 --> 14:12.310
I may have mentioned
that it's a little inappropriate...

14:12.477 --> 14:15.480
...to be asking another man's girlfriend
to his experiment...

14:15.647 --> 14:17.649
...without discussing it with said man.

14:17.816 --> 14:20.610
I need to ask your permission
to hang outwith Leonard?

14:20.777 --> 14:26.408
I didn't say anything like that.
I said Leonard has to ask my permission.

14:28.076 --> 14:31.955
Come on, I don't wanna eat lamb stew
with my mother.

14:32.914 --> 14:35.917
Damn. Was this close on the bra.

14:38.295 --> 14:41.673
Now, remember, Newton realized
that Aristotle was wrong...

14:41.840 --> 14:44.426
...and force was not necessary
to maintain motion.

14:44.593 --> 14:47.888
So let's plug in our 9.8 meters
per second squared...

14:48.054 --> 14:51.349
...as A and we get force--
Earth gravity.

14:51.516 --> 14:54.853
--Equals mass times
9.8 meters per second per second.

14:55.020 --> 14:59.399
So we can see that MA equals MG
and what do we know from this?

15:03.570 --> 15:08.617
Uh... We know that Newton
was a really smart cookie.

15:10.285 --> 15:13.163
Oh, is that where Fig Newtons
come from?

15:13.872 --> 15:17.209
No, Fig Newtons are named
after a small town in Massachusetts.

15:17.918 --> 15:20.629
- No, don't write that down.
- Sorry.

15:21.046 --> 15:23.340
Now, if MA equals MG...

15:23.507 --> 15:25.592
- ...what does that imply?
- I don't know.

15:25.759 --> 15:28.345
What--? But--?
How can you not know? I just told you.

15:28.512 --> 15:31.264
Have you suffered
a recent blow to the head?

15:31.890 --> 15:34.184
Hey, you don't have to be so mean.

15:34.351 --> 15:38.271
I'm sorry. Have you suffered
a recent blow to the head?

15:40.857 --> 15:42.609
No. You just suck at teaching.

15:42.776 --> 15:45.987
Really? Of those two explanations,
which one seems the most likely?

15:46.154 --> 15:47.614
Oh, God.

15:47.781 --> 15:51.368
Sheldon, look, I'm trying to understand
but you're going too fast.

15:51.535 --> 15:55.789
- Can you just back up a little bit?
- All right.

15:55.997 --> 15:59.209
It's a warm summer evening
in ancient Greece--

15:59.376 --> 16:00.877
Not that far back.

16:01.044 --> 16:04.631
Okay, at what point
did you begin to feel lost?

16:04.798 --> 16:07.759
I don't know. Where were we looking up
at the night sky?

16:07.926 --> 16:10.011
- Greece.
- Damn it.

16:10.178 --> 16:12.097
Look,
there's no need to get frustrated.

16:12.264 --> 16:14.015
People learn at different rates.

16:14.182 --> 16:18.853
Unlike objects falling in a vacuum,
which...?

16:21.147 --> 16:23.858
MA equals MG...?

16:24.317 --> 16:26.444
- Squared?
- No.

16:27.112 --> 16:29.406
- Aristotle?
- No.

16:29.823 --> 16:31.449
- Five?
- Oh!

16:31.783 --> 16:35.078
Oh, then I don't know.

16:36.413 --> 16:39.916
- Why are you crying?
- Because I'm stupid.

16:40.083 --> 16:42.168
Well, that's no reason to cry.

16:43.461 --> 16:45.380
No, one cries because one is sad.

16:45.547 --> 16:50.260
For example, I cry because
others are stupid and it makes me sad.

16:51.803 --> 16:54.806
Look, can we just please forget
about all this extra stuff...

16:54.973 --> 16:57.601
...and can you just tell me
what Leonard does?

16:57.767 --> 16:58.852
All right.

16:59.019 --> 17:01.563
Leonard is attempting to learn...

17:01.730 --> 17:04.316
...why subatomic particles
move the way they do.

17:05.317 --> 17:08.903
Really? That's it?
Well, that doesn't sound so complicated.

17:09.070 --> 17:12.282
It's not. That's why Leonard does it.

17:15.118 --> 17:16.995
Okay, I just have one question.

17:17.162 --> 17:19.706
What exactly are subatomic particles?

17:19.873 --> 17:22.751
- A good question.
- Thank you.

17:22.917 --> 17:26.046
And to answer it, we first must
ask ourselves, "What is physics?"

17:26.212 --> 17:27.631
Oh, balls.

17:27.797 --> 17:30.675
It's a warm summer evening
in ancient Greece.

17:32.510 --> 17:34.679
Okay, I got a bone to pick with you.

17:34.971 --> 17:36.139
What did I do now?

17:36.306 --> 17:39.809
I was in bed with Bernadette
and you text-blocked me.

17:40.852 --> 17:43.188
- What?
- Yeah, we were completely naked...

17:43.355 --> 17:44.981
...and about to devour each other
when:

17:45.148 --> 17:46.358
[IMITATES CELL PHONE CHIMING]

17:46.524 --> 17:49.235
You text her that I have a problem
with her hanging with you.

17:49.402 --> 17:52.530
You do have a problem with her
hanging out with me.

17:52.697 --> 17:54.491
But that's not what you tell her.

17:54.658 --> 17:56.618
- What was I to tell her?
- I don't know.

17:56.785 --> 18:00.664
Something that doesn't make me
come off as a petty, jealous douche.

18:01.665 --> 18:03.917
And what would that be?

18:05.919 --> 18:08.713
Come on,
do I have to think of everything?

18:09.255 --> 18:11.758
Hey, Leonard,
am I too late to see your experiment?

18:12.509 --> 18:14.511
- Oh, hi.
- Hi.

18:14.678 --> 18:17.472
- What are you doing here?
- Same thing you're doing here.

18:17.639 --> 18:20.642
- Came to see Leonard's experiment.
- No, you didn't.

18:20.809 --> 18:22.769
You said Leonard's experiment
was stupid.

18:24.104 --> 18:25.355
[HOWARD SIGHS]

18:26.856 --> 18:29.192
You told her my experiment
was stupid?

18:29.484 --> 18:31.528
I was just repeating
what Sheldon said.

18:32.696 --> 18:37.033
Look, let's not get off topic.
Bernadette, I need to apologize.

18:37.200 --> 18:40.537
You know, I was wrong to tell you
who you should be friends with.

18:40.704 --> 18:44.416
- Should I leave you two alone?
- No, Leonard, you should hear this.

18:44.582 --> 18:47.377
Okay, good.
Because I wasn't really gonna go.

18:48.086 --> 18:53.633
Look, I know I come off
as confident and worldly...

18:55.135 --> 18:56.928
...but the truth is I'm not.

18:57.095 --> 18:58.930
We're shocked.

19:00.390 --> 19:04.144
Which is why I tend to feel threatened
by other guys.

19:04.310 --> 19:08.064
Or loud noises, clowns and nuns.

19:09.983 --> 19:12.652
But I now realize how foolish that is.

19:12.819 --> 19:16.281
He had a panic attack once
when he got his head stuck in his sweater.

19:17.574 --> 19:20.201
It was a full turtleneck.

19:20.368 --> 19:22.829
- And why aren't you helping me?
- I don't know.

19:22.996 --> 19:26.249
Maybe because I'm crazy?

19:30.128 --> 19:33.590
Bernadette, please, I'm asking you
to give me another chance.

19:33.882 --> 19:37.343
What do you think, Leonard?
Should I give him another chance?

19:37.510 --> 19:40.305
It's up to you.
He didn't call your experiment stupid.

19:42.432 --> 19:43.683
Come here, tushy-face.

19:43.850 --> 19:45.518
[BOTH CHUCKLE]

19:45.727 --> 19:49.147
Tushy-face.
That is going on Twitter right now.

19:55.195 --> 19:57.697
Raj, you should've seen
Leonard's experiment.

19:57.864 --> 20:00.950
The interference pattern was cool
when the electron beam was on.

20:01.117 --> 20:05.288
I'm glad you enjoyed it. Most people
aren't that interested in what I do.

20:10.251 --> 20:11.419
[CLEARS THROAT]

20:11.586 --> 20:13.713
Actually, that's not true, Leonard.

20:13.880 --> 20:17.091
I've been thinking that, given
the parameters of your experiment...

20:17.258 --> 20:20.428
...the transport of electrons
through the nano-fabricated rings...

20:20.595 --> 20:25.016
...is no different than the experiment
already conducted in the Netherlands.

20:27.602 --> 20:31.064
Their observed phase shift in
the diffusing electrons inside the ring...

20:31.231 --> 20:33.399
...already demonstrated
the electric analogue...

20:33.566 --> 20:36.402
...of the Aharonov-Bohm
quantum interference effect.

20:41.991 --> 20:44.244
That's it. That's all I know.

20:45.286 --> 20:46.538
Oh, wait.

20:47.497 --> 20:51.292
Fig Newtons were named after a town
in Massachusetts, not the scientist.

21:22.240 --> 21:24.242
[ENGLISH - US - SDH]
